    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-cou2-vr-03-hemolysis-index",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Absolute normalised index of haemolysis (NIH) prediction validation across all five flow-speed operating conditions with Monte Carlo uncertainty bands",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis",
      "description": "CFD-predicted NIH values were computed using the power-law hemolysis damage model (Giersiepen et al. coefficients) integrated along Lagrangian particle paths seeded at the inlet for each of the five operating points (2 L/min at 2500 RPM; 3 L/min at 3000 RPM; 4 L/min at 3500 RPM; 5 L/min at 4000 RPM; 6 L/min at 4500 RPM). Monte Carlo sampling (N=2000 draws) was applied to the model coefficients α, β, and C, propagating parameter uncertainty through to NIH. Predicted mean NIH values fell within 18% of the experimental measurements at four of five operating points; the fifth point (6 L/min, 4500 RPM) exhibited a 31% over-prediction attributed to impeller tip-clearance sensitivity. The validation team reviewed raw simulation output files, experimental haematology assay reports, and the UQ sweep logs during a formal validation review meeting held on 14 November 2024. All artefacts were archived to the project document management system. The review concluded that the model demonstrates adequate predictive accuracy for absolute hemolysis at the four lower operating points, with a documented gap at the highest flow-speed condition that is captured as a credibility factor gap rather than a validation failure."
    }
  ],
